text.html: Dojo Has it Large in... Kentish Town
text.text: Dojo Has it Large in... Kentish Town

More grownup than Camden but less ‘Hunter welly crew’ than Primrose Hill, Kentish Town is a nice middle ground where independent coffee shops reign supreme, cocktail bars get stuck in public toilets and retired Camden punks still frequent traditional pubs. We’ve been having it large in K-Town this week - here's what we found.
Best for... squeezing into a beer garden

tip.text: If it’s an elaborate drink you’re after, craft beer haunt The Rose and Crown will most definitely have you covered. Boasting an inspiringly eclectic lineup of rotating bevvies and ever honing the spotlight on small, local and quite often crazy breweries – you can expect to wrap your gob around everything from shortbread-flavoured beer to tropical punch-flavoured beer and everything in between. Also on the cards is an incredibly unique and innovative snack menu, live music, comedy nights and a spectacularly dingy, club-like basement that’s available for hire.

text.text:
If it’s an elaborate drink in the sunshine you’re after, craft beer haunt The Rose and Crown will most definitely have you covered. Boasting an eclectic lineup of rotating bevvies and ever honing the spotlight on small, local and quite often crazy breweries – expect to wrap your gob around everything from shortbread-flavoured ale to tropical punch-flavoured lager and everything in between. 

Also on the cards is an incredibly unique and innovative snack menu, live music, comedy nights, a cosy beer patio and a spectacularly dingy, club-like basement that’s available for hire. Also, the staff are really fucking nice.

tip.text:
Paris may only be two hours away, but for Jean-François, Tanzi and Natty, that’s about an hour and fifty five minutes too far. They wanted good wine, good cheese, good charcuterie, and they wanted it now.

So they came up with Patron, the wine shop and deli-bar, minutes away from Patron, the restaurant. Here, you can sit at the Harvest table with your date, sip on some wine, nibble on some camembert and chow down on some saucisson. You can find out where your wine comes from, how it was made, how much it costs. Then you can buy the bottle and take it home, along with your date - or not.

If you're a charcuterie nerd like us you might want to feast your eyes on this list: terrine, jambon de Bayonne, duck rillettes, walnut saucisson, 4 month coppa, fennel salami, sun dried chilli salami and all served with cornichons, caper berries and pain de campagne. The stuff a carnivore's dreams are made of.

Best for... good coffee and vegan goods

tip.text:
Housed beneath the station arches, this tiny - like really, really tiny - homely coffeehouse is the perfect spot to sip on some artisan coffee and chit chat with locals. With its long communal table, quirky brick walls and mosaics, this little gem champions cosy vibes, homemade pastries and all-vegan goods - so no, you cannot have milk in your coffee because they're saving the cows, one cuppa at a time.

A firm favourite of London vegans, The Fields Beneath offers some pretty inventive breakfast and lunch options. They've got it all from fresh pastries, to tempeh baps. A croissant filled with marmite, mushroom and sage for you? You'll either love it or hate it...

tip.text:
From 19th century coaching house to top London gastropub, the Bull & Last is famed for its Sunday roasts and modern European cuisine, but we just stopped by for snacks - the saucisson with cornichons and impossibly crispy pig cheeks served with watermelon pickle and a basil and sesame dressing were seriously good, and their scotch eggs are legendary.

The pub downstairs is dog-friendly and has all the ales you'll need, while upstairs is more of a restaurant kinda thing. Situated seconds from Hampstead Heath, this is the perfect place to come for a pre-/post-walk in the park or just a lazy afternoon of indulgence.

tip.text: While Tufnell Park is by no means short of banging pubs, The Pineapple might just take the biscuit. Tucked away from the buzz of the main road yet fantastically rowdy in its own right – the spectacular crew behind this North London boozer know exactly what’s up. This beautiful listed building is home to guaranteed romping good times, with ‘Cheese Thursdays’ (donate £3 to a colossal pub cheeseboard and dig in knowing your change is going to the homeless), a stellar Thai kitchen upstairs and £5 lunches. Oh, and there’s two pub cats with a penchant for prawns and scuttling around the place. Meow.

Best for... beef and a brew

tip.text:
Dig the fact that you can get now get a decent steak for a tenner in London? What if we told you you could get a killer steak for that sum, accompanied by an impressive beer menu and sides like brisket jam nuggets, smoked pigs cheek on toast, and gnocchi ’n’ cheese with jalapeños?

At surface level, Beef & Brew ticks all the boxes - the buzz of a good neighbourhood restaurant, friendly and knowledgable service, simple but effective decor. But it’s the tender, delicious hanger steak with truffle béarnaise sauce and the aforementioned accompaniments that elevates this to vital status.

tip.text:
Getting pissed in an old pisser might not sound too glam, but Ladies and Gentlemen in Kentish Town proves that with the right people behind it, any venue can come good. Heading down into this wee (heh) cocktail bar feels dead novel, but when you get inside it's clearly legit.

Old cisterns on the wall remind you of the bar's damp past, but the Pisco Sour they mix up here makes you forget all about that. Using honey from Kentish Town and picking their own fresh fruits from their allotment in Hampstead, the lovely people behind this place are well aware that the devil is in the detail. Try and spot the little copper still that they use for making their own spirits too.

tip.text:
Every aspect of this pub feels like a direct push-back against the corporate, chain, soulless, Fosters-serving, beer-and-burger-deal-having, laminated-menu megapub fuckery that has no doubt taken over your old local. These guys are serving strictly real ales and ciders from independent suppliers (they do wine and spirit-mixers but they look at you funny when you order them); they only take cash; and for food they have a small range of tasty pies, scotch eggs, and pork belly sandwiches served with a crusty-as-all-hell roll and punchy piccalilli.

Now, before you start scoffing and muttering ‘hipster’ you should know that this is maybe the least pretentious pub we've been to. It’s mostly just old ale enthusiasts chilling the fuck out on repurposed church furniture - or in the teeny back garden - and basking in their love of all things curmudgeonly.

text.text:
This relaxed, homely venue has a mission. They only stock beers and ciders from small independent uk breweries. So you can drink the likes of Brew by Numbers, Brick Brewery, Five Points and One Mile End. The decor is real nice too, no swirly carpets that make you feel too drunk before you are, just repurposed church benches, some lovely tileage and a mismatched collection of paintings. Yeah we like. 

Be warned though it's a cash only bar. Woah retro!

tip.text:
You could easily walk past this tiny restaurant in Kentish Town, it looks like a pretty run of the mill café from the outside, but seriously don’t. There’s some serious Italian cooking hiding in there, and you need to stuff yourself silly with it.

The menu changes constantly, with the likes of polenta and fresh pasta making regular appearances, but really it's the homemade desserts that have us crawling back and begging for more. Like the tiramisu.. OMFG the tiramisu... It's also BYOB, so stop off and get a bottle or two or three or however many you'll need to wash down all the carbs and sugary treats - they won't charge you to open it. You might want to pick up some liquid luck too, there are only about ten tables to be had and the locals are on it.
